english:
  title: Portrait
  author: Lee Gyeou-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    My beard is coarse and disheveled,
    my lips thick and ruddy—
    who is this man in the mirror?
    He seems to resemble Chun-gyeong.
    If it is indeed Chun-gyeong,
    is it shadow or substance?
    Substance itself is but illusion,
    no more real than a dream.
    How much less so is a shadow—
    a dream within a dream.

    Through fifty years of rising and falling,
    this humble frame of mine
    has been set into silk.
    There I stand, seemingly solid,
    yet capturing the heart is difficult—
    only faintly does it show through in the portrait.

    To all my descendants, I say:
    do not laugh at your ancestor's ugly face.
    Just pass on this heart of mine,
    and you will bring no shame to those who came before.
  footnotes:
    - Chun-gyeong (춘경) likely refers to the artist's own name or self-reference, suggesting this is a poem about a self-portrait
    - The phrase 'dream within a dream' echoes Buddhist and Daoist philosophical concepts of the illusory nature of reality prevalent in medieval Korean thought
    - The 'fifty years' (오십 년) marks a significant life milestone in East Asian tradition, representing maturity and reflection
